Right, I see. The problem is the single thread consuming everything into one big lock-protected vector at once. When messages arrive quickly but processing happens in series instead of parallel bursts, we get this massive latency spike.

// Refactored version - using a task pool
use tokio::{net::TcpListener, sync::mpsc};

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    let port = 8080;

    // Create separate channels for each message instead of one big block
    let mut channels = Vec::new();
    for (index, msg) in stream.into_iter().enumerate() {
        if let Some(tx) = channels.last_mut() {
            let payload = msg.payload.clone();
            drop(tx); // Signal end of this batch to next one
            tx.send(payload);
        }
    }

    // Run all small batches in parallel using a task pool (not just one worker)
    tokio::task::spawn_blocking(|| {
        let aggregator = BatchAggregator::new();
        for (index, msg) in stream.into_iter().enumerate() {
            if let Some(tx) = channels.last_mut() {
                drop(tx); // Signal end of this batch to next one
                tx.send(msg.payload.clone());
            }
        }
    })
    .await;

    println!("Batch processing complete!");
}

Wait, that's not quite right either. The `add_payload` needs to return a channel so the next batch can send its messages to it. And we need to keep sending until we've received all data from this message.
